---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "Is organic coffee worth the extra cost?",
    a: "For most specialty drinkers, yes, but not strictly because of the chemical-free claim. The reason organic coffee tends to be worth the premium is that the same farms willing to absorb the cost and complexity of certification (3-year transition period, annual inspections, separated processing) are usually also the farms invested in slower, higher-quality cultivation: shade canopies, healthier soil biology, and producer relationships that pay growers more per pound. You are paying for the practices around the certification at least as much as the certification itself. If your only goal is cheap caffeine, organic is not worth it. If your goal is a clean, well-grown, well-roasted cup with a transparent supply chain, organic is one of the best filters available."
  },
  {
    q: "Does organic coffee taste different from conventional?",
    a: "Sometimes, but the difference is rarely the absence of chemical residue you can taste in the cup. What you actually taste is the cultivation system. Organic coffee is usually shade-grown or partially shaded, which slows cherry development and concentrates sugars. The soil tends to be richer in organic matter because synthetic nitrogen is banned, so growers use compost and cover crops. Both of those produce denser, sweeter, more complex beans. The flavor edge attributed to organic is really the edge of slower, healthier growing. A conventional farm using identical practices minus the certification can produce a cup that tastes equally good."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between organic and shade-grown coffee?",
    a: "Organic is a chemical standard. Shade-grown is a cultivation standard. Organic coffee can be grown in full sun under high-input organic conditions, and shade-grown coffee can be sprayed with synthetic pesticides if the grower chooses (it is not automatically organic). The strictest overlap is Smithsonian Bird Friendly certification, which requires both organic cultivation AND a specific canopy density with native tree species. If you want both protections (no synthetic chemicals and a habitat-supporting shade canopy), look for Bird Friendly certification specifically, not just organic."
  },
  {
    q: "Is decaf coffee ever organic?",
    a: "Yes, and it matters more here than with caffeinated coffee. Conventional decaf is often processed using methylene chloride, an industrial solvent the FDA permits for coffee decaffeination in trace amounts. USDA Organic certification bans methylene chloride decaffeination entirely. Organic decaf must use Swiss Water Process, CO2 process, or ethyl acetate from natural sources (the so-called sugar cane process). If you drink decaf regularly, choosing an organic-certified decaf is the cleanest way to avoid solvent residue without having to research each roaster's decaffeination method individually."
  },
  {
    q: "Why isn't more coffee organic?",
    a: "Three reasons. First, certification cost: the 3-year transition period means a farm pays for organic practices for 3 years before it can sell at organic prices, which is financially impossible for many smallholder farmers without external support. Second, yield: organic coffee farms typically produce 20 to 40 percent less per acre than conventional farms using synthetic nitrogen, so growers need a premium price to make the economics work. Third, processing infrastructure: every step from farm to wet mill to dry mill to export to roastery has to be separately certified to maintain organic status, which is logistically complex. The result is that organic coffee is a minority of global production, concentrated among either premium specialty growers or cooperatives with NGO support."
  },
  {
    q: "Is single-origin organic better than an organic blend?",
    a: "Neither is inherently better; they serve different purposes. Single-origin organic gives you a transparent terroir experience: you can taste the specific region, altitude, and processing method. Organic blends prioritize consistency, balance, and often a more accessible price point because the roaster can shift component lots seasonally without changing the blend's overall profile. For exploring origins and processing styles, single-origin organic is the way to go (start with our single-origin coffee guide). For a reliable everyday cup at a friendlier price, an organic blend from a sustainability-focused roaster is the more practical choice."
  }
];

